A warning was sent to residents via the NERV Disaster Prevention App. The earthquake's epicentre struck around near the island of Taiwan at 15:22 local time (7:22 BST). It was originally estimated to be a magnitude 7.7 or higher, according to the Japan Meteorological Agency, before being raised to "above 7.9 magnitude".  The alert read: "This is an Earthquake Early Warning. There is only a short time before a strong shake comes. "Please check the timeline after ensuring safety. Be careful of things that fall from above or fall down. "Please put out fires after the shaking has subsided." Experts said residents in Yaeyama Miyakojima could expect to feel "very strong shaking". They added that there was a "risk of a tsunami". The alert said: "Be careful of tsunamis near the swaying coast and the mouth of the river just in case." The German Research Centre for Geosciences (GFZ) reported a magnitude 6.1 quake in Japan near Hualien City, Hualien, Taiwan. France's Réseau National de Surveillance Sismique (RéNaSS) listed the quake at magnitude 5.8. A third agency, the European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre (EMSC), reported the same quake with a magnitude 6.5. the island’s east coast, roughly halfway between Hualien county and the southern Japanese island of Yonaguni. The quake was felt across Taiwan. Authorities later confirmed there was no danger of a tsunami. Taiwan lies near the junction of two tectonic plates and is prone to earthquakes. More than 100 people were killed in a quake in southern Taiwan in 2016, while a 7.3 magnitude quake killed more than 2,000 people in 1999.